>>47307376
>do you have any tips for writing in the first person?
I'd say "don't", because I don't like it. So I can really go into my pet peeve with it: Most people don't really seem to have in mind why and how they want to use the first person narrator. It invokes a strong feeling of journal-type storytelling, or some other form of the narrator relating the tale later, but that's not how many people use it. They just use it as any other narrator. I like to listen to shitty creepypasta/nosleep stories on YouTube, and one had a perfect example of why this shit jars the fuck out of me: The genre is mostly first person because of the gimmick, many are supposed to be "real" stories related later by the narrator. So this is the expectation when a story is in first person. But then the narrator dies at the end. So it wasn't a relaying of the story, and the perspective was a red herring.

In the published fiction I've read, I think there has been only one in first person that I considered good. But definitely not among the best. And it very clearly uses the perspective as the narrator relaying the story of his crimes and capture later, in his cell. I've read non-fiction that was in first person, which was good. But all of the best fiction was third person.

So I think it's weird. To do well, it's hard. But many authors seem to use it as a crutch. That was the feel I got from all the shitty books I read that were first person.

Anonymous Fri 29 Apr 2022 11:43:02 No.47310534 Report
Quoted By: >>47311228 >>47311529
>>47309852
First person works well in some genres & subgenres.
I've written both, and it always comes down to which narrator is going to tell the story best and which will be best to show you the setting.
If you're highly biased toward one, you'd probably look at a story in the other and say that it could be in your preferred POV. And then it would be a completely different story. If it loses the subtext the writer intended for the narrator to show you, and in the way, then that's not good.
Take Amerian Psycho, which most here will be familiar with through the movie. The book is a completely different beast. I feel as though I'm supposed to laugh at the movie, but the underlying horror is lost compared to the book.

First person was the standard at one time. Hemingway wrote in both, and I take example from him. Get out of the way of the story. Don't throw away half your tools. The characters will do the rest.
